{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e8b29402-e771-4ed2-95f0-f6e60cd393d0","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the OS automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (if you need one for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited        # enable core dumps for the session\n/usr/libexec/PlistBuddy -c \"Print :com.apple.CrashReporter.DirectoryInfo\" \\\n  /Library/Preferences/com.apple.CrashReporter.plist   # check core dump path\n```\n\nCore dumps are typically written to `/cores/core.<pid>` (requires SIP adjustments on modern macOS).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"70829384-90c7-4e5c-9da7-4d4b139c15c6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no code changes needed.","outputTokens":330},"id":"3ef2ebdb-0c05-4599-a71b-f8108935b012","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:55:35.880Z","parentId":"3680fda6-e638-4751-9253-0a7653258a42"}
